{{Infobox institute | name = Marine Science Institute | image = File:Marine Science Institute SF Bay Logo.png | image_upright = | alt = Marine Science Institute | caption = Marine Science Institute Logo | latin_name = | motto = Discovering Our Bay | founder = | established = {{Start date and age|1970}}<ref name="sfg">{{cite news|last1=Tucker|first1=Jill|title=Marine Science Institute gives youths up-close look at oil spill|url=http://www.sfgate.com/education/article/Marine-Science-Institute-gives-youths-up-close-3234805.php|accessdate=2 December 2016|work=SFGate|date=17 November 2007}}</ref> | mission = Cultivate a responsibility for the natural environment and our human communities through interdisciplinary science education. | focus = Marine Education | president = | ceo = | chairman = James Crawford<ref name="issu">{{cite web|last1=Murzi-Moyce|first1=Tiff|title=BayLines|url=https://issuu.com/sfbaymsi/docs/baylines_fall_2016|accessdate=2 December 2016|date=2016}}</ref> | head_label = Executive Director | head = Marilou Seiff | faculty = | adjunct_faculty = | staff = | key_people = | budget = {{Currency|1775000|US}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Annual Report 2015|url=http://media.wix.com/ugd/74faa6_3c2f5f9939d148bfa902662d62daebac.pdf|publisher=Marine Science Institute|accessdate=1 December 2016|date=2015}}</ref> | endowment = | debt = | num_members = | subsidiaries = | owner = | non-profit_slogan = | former_name = | location = | city = [[Redwood City, California|Redwood City]] | state = California | province = | country = US | coor = {{coord|37.504859|-122.217147|region:US-CA_type:landmark_scale:40000|format=dms|display=it}} | address = 500 Discovery Parkway, Redwood City, CA 94063<ref name="loc">{{cite web|title=Directions|url=http://www.sfbaymsi.org/directions|website=Marine Science Institute|accessdate=1 December 2016}}</ref> | website = {{Official URL}} | dissolved = | footnotes = }}
The '''Marine Science Institute''' (MSI) is a [[nonprofit organization]] focusing on [[marine science]] research and education. MSI was founded in 1970<ref name="sfg"/> and currently is situated in [[Redwood City, California]] adjacent to the [[Port of Redwood City]].<ref name="loc"/> In the [[San Francisco Bay Area]] MSI has a mission driving marine education for schoolchildren and continues to receive grants to supplement their donations.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Californial Coastal Conservancy|authorlink1=California Coastal Conservancy|title=Explore The Coast Grants Program|url=http://scc.ca.gov/webmaster/ftp/pdf/sccbb/2016/1603/20160324Board10_Explore_the_Coast|accessdate=2 December 2016|pages=11|date=24 March 2016}}</ref>
==Education and research== The Marine Science Institute offers tours of the Bay in [[Antioch, California|Antioch]] in the January and February months, and the rest of the time based out of Redwood City at their main location and research station along the banks of [[Redwood Creek (San Mateo County)|Redwood Creek]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Jason B.|title=Voyage of Delta discoveries|url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Voyage-of-Delta-discoveries-Redwood-City-2772193.php|accessdate=2 December 2016|work=SFGate|date=2 April 2004}}</ref> The institute allows students at schools around the bay to observe and interact with the natural environment.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Walsh|first1=Austin|title=Tech aims to sponsor field trips: Redwood City students get trip through new program|url=http://www.smdailyjournal.com/articles/lnews/2016-03-19/tech-aims-to-sponsor-field-trips-redwood-city-students-get-trip-through-new-program/1776425160336.html|accessdate=2 December 2016|work=San Mateo Daily Journal|date=19 March 2016}}</ref>Marine life is often collected, measured for size, and documented to add to a database to continually monitor conditions and overall health within the bay. MSI also trains teachers in integrating technology and science into their own curriculums.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yamamoto|first1=Nancy|title=Science Lab in San Mateo County – Classroom by the Bay|url=https://ww2.kqed.org/learning/2012/07/30/science-lab-in-san-mateo-county-classroom-by-the-bay/|website=KQED|accessdate=2 December 2016|date=30 July 2012}}</ref> The Marine Science Institute also hosts an [[Earth Day]] celebration annually.<ref>{{cite news|title=Port sponsors family-friendly events: Sailing, STEM festival and Earth Day event mark busy Saturday|url=http://www.smdailyjournal.com/articles/lnews/2016-04-15/port-sponsors-family-friendly-events-sailing-stem-festival-and-earth-day-event-mark-busy-saturday/1776425161787.html|accessdate=2 December 2016|work=San Mateo Daily News|date=15 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Earth Day Events in the Bay Area|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2012/04/19/earth-day-events-in-the-bay-area-2/|accessdate=2 December 2016|work=San Jose Mercury News|date=19 April 2012}}</ref> Other events organized by MSI include coastal hikes, cleanups, tide walks, and voyages for the general public.<ref name="issu"/>
==''Robert G. Brownlee''== The {{convert|90|ft|m|adj=on}} by {{convert|30|ft|m|adj=on}} [[research vessel]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bartlett|first1=Jean|title=Making science fun — Skyline teacher emphasizes the cultivation of wonder|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2012/11/20/making-science-fun-skyline-teacher-emphasizes-the-cultivation-of-wonder/|accessdate=2 December 2016|work=San Jose Mercury News|date=20 November 2012}}</ref> built to satisfy the needs of MSI was named after [[Robert Brownlee]] whose foundation donated funds for the vessel. Construction of the steel vessel with hull depth of {{convert|11.8|ft|m|adj=on}}, hull 474,<ref>{{cite web|title=USCG Doc. No.: 1065176|url=http://www.st.nmfs.noaa.gov/st1/CoastGuard/VesselByName.html|publisher=USCG Vessel Documentation Center|accessdate=8 December 2016|date=16 March 2016}}</ref> was completed by the Marco Shipyards in [[Seattle]] in 1998.<ref>{{cite book|title=Ship & Boat International|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q2NWAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=2 December 2016|year=1998|publisher=Pax Marine Press AB}}</ref> Original specifications for the craft had a propulsion system, that could reach 12 [[knot (unit)|knots]], comprising two {{convert|860|mm|in|adj=on}} propellers driven by a pair of 250 [[horsepower]] Cummins diesels. The vessel, which can fit up to 70 students, has facilities for several science activities including studying [[plankton]] and fish with holding tanks below deck as well as running [[hydrology]] tests.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lowrey|first1=Angela|title=Research Vessel Robert G. Brownlee|url=http://www.deltadiablo.org/services/community-outreach-education-programs/research-vessel-robert-g-brownlee|website=Delta Diablo|accessdate=2 December 2016}}</ref> Following the [[Cosco Busan oil spill]] the vessel was used to take children out showing the damage the [[San Francisco–Oakland Bay Bridge|Bay Bridge]] suffered firsthand as well as take comparative data on how the spill affected marine life in the area.<ref name="sfg"/>
